&lt;div class="prompt input_prompt"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="inner_cell"&gt;
&lt;div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html"&gt;
&lt;h3 id="Introduction"&gt;Introduction&lt;a class="anchor-link" href="http://colour-science.org/posts/about-rgb-colourspace-models-performance/#Introduction"&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"&gt;
&lt;div class="prompt input_prompt"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="inner_cell"&gt;
&lt;div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The purpose of this document is to compare &lt;em&gt;RGB&lt;/em&gt; colourspace models operations performance against spectral reference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Various mathematical operations because of the nature of matrices and linear algebra are dependent on given &lt;em&gt;RGB&lt;/em&gt; colourspace primaries. The same operations performed in different &lt;em&gt;RGB&lt;/em&gt; colourspaces will yield different tristimulus values once converted back to &lt;em&gt;CIE XYZ&lt;/em&gt; colourspace. For example &lt;em&gt;multiplication&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;division&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;power&lt;/em&gt; operations are &lt;em&gt;RGB&lt;/em&gt; colourspace primaries dependent while &lt;em&gt;addition&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;subtraction&lt;/em&gt; are not.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;em&gt;rgb_colourspace_primaries_dependency&lt;/em&gt; definition below demonstrates this behaviour: Two colours are selected from the colour rendition chart, they are then used as operands for different operations happening respectively in &lt;em&gt;sRGB&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Rec. 2020&lt;/em&gt; colourspaces. The two resulting colours are then converted back to &lt;em&gt;CIE XYZ&lt;/em&gt; colourspace and compared.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note: A companion spreadsheet is available at the following url: &lt;a href="http://goo.gl/akrH5m"&gt;http://goo.gl/akrH5m&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
